  "opinion": "As a 20-year-old woman working as a mechanic in Milan, I’ve noticed how deeply the gender gap in science affects real-world opportunities. Growing up in a family where my father has a PhD and my mother has an upper secondary education, I was exposed to both scientific curiosity and the societal expectations that often steer girls away from STEM fields. The gap isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the invisible barriers that make it harder for women to thrive in science. For instance, in my part-time job, I see how many girls my age are discouraged from pursuing technical roles because they’re told ‘science isn’t for girls.’ This stereotype isn’t just harmful; it’s a direct result of systemic biases that start early. I believe we must address this gap, not through grand gestures but by creating inclusive spaces where women feel empowered to explore science without fear. In my city, there are few female-led science workshops for teenagers, which means many girls miss out on hands-on learning opportunities. By partnering with schools and community centers to offer gender-inclusive STEM programs, we can help bridge this divide. It’s not about forcing everyone into a single path—it’s about ensuring that every girl has the chance to discover her passion, whether it’s physics, biology, or even mechanics. As someone who’s creative and often finds inspiration in nature through birdwatching, I see science as a way to understand the world around us. Addressing the gender gap isn’t just ethical—it’s necessary for innovation. If we want to build a future where everyone can contribute to science, we need to start by listening to the voices of those who are often silenced.",
